  "prompt": "Can I deactivate my Roku device?",
  "response": "Yes, you can deactivate your Roku device, which is often referred to as unlinking or factory resetting. Here's how to do it, along with information on what happens when you do:\n\n**Methods for Deactivating/Unlinking a Roku Device:**\n\n1.  **From the Roku Device Itself (Recommended):**\n\n    *   **Factory Reset:** This is the most thorough way to deactivate a Roku. It removes all personal settings, linked accounts, installed channels, and returns the device to its original, out-of-the-box state.\n\n        *   **Steps:**\n            1.  Go to **Settings**.\n            2.  Select **System**.\n            3.  Select **Advanced system settings**. (On some older models, it might be under \"System restart\" or \"Advanced Settings\")\n            4.  Select **Factory reset**.\n            5.  Follow the on-screen prompts.  You'll typically be asked to confirm your decision.  It may take several minutes to complete.\n\n2.  **Through Your Roku Account on the Roku Website:**\n\n    *   While there's no direct \"deactivate device\" button on the website, removing the device from your account can be achieved by factory resetting it. Once reset, the device will no longer be linked to your account.  If the device is not accessible, you can remove all devices from your account, and then reactivate only the devices you still have.\n\n**What Happens When You Deactivate/Unlink a Roku:**\n\n*   **Device is Removed from Your Account:** The Roku will no longer be associated with your Roku account.\n*   **Channel Data is Removed:** All of your installed channels and their associated data (login information, viewing preferences, etc.) will be removed from the device.\n*   **Personal Settings are Reset:** Your display settings, network settings, and other personal preferences will be reset to their default values.\n*   **Subscription Billing is Unaffected:** Deactivating the Roku device *does not* cancel any subscriptions you've made through Roku (e.g., Roku Channel subscriptions). You must manage those subscriptions separately through your Roku account online.\n*   **The Device Can Be Reactivated:** The Roku device itself is not disabled. You or someone else can link it to a new Roku account and set it up again.\n*   **Roku Pay Information is *Not* Removed:** A factory reset does *not* remove your payment information stored on your Roku account. Your payment information is tied to your overall Roku account, not to a specific device. To manage or remove your payment information, you must do so through your Roku account on the Roku website.\n\n**Important Considerations:**\n\n*   **Before Selling or Giving Away a Roku:** Always perform a factory reset *before* selling, donating, or giving away a Roku device. This protects your personal information.\n*   **Subscription Management:**  Double-check your Roku account online to cancel any Roku-billed subscriptions *before* deactivating the device, especially if you're no longer going to use it. Go to my.roku.com and sign in to your account. You can manage your subscriptions there.\n*   **Lost or Stolen Devices:** If your Roku device has been lost or stolen, factory resetting it remotely is not possible.  All you can do is unlink your account, which would prevent anyone from using your payment information (although they can still create a new account and use the device).  You will need to remove the card from your Roku Account as well.\n*   **Troubleshooting:** Sometimes, a factory reset can resolve certain issues with a Roku device.  If you're having problems, it's worth trying a reset before contacting Roku support.\n*   **Remote Issues:** If you don't have the remote for your Roku, many Roku devices have a physical reset button on the device itself. Hold the reset button for 30 seconds and the device will factory reset.\n\nIn summary, factory resetting your Roku is the best way to deactivate it, ensuring your personal information is removed and the device is ready for a new user or for storage. Don't forget to manage your subscriptions separately through your Roku account.\n",
